            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Nikolai Orlov is a product of his parents\u2019 ambition. The only child of Russian immigrants who uprooted their lives from St. Petersburg in the mid-90s, he was raised in the foggy avenues of San Francisco's Richmond District. His father, a former engineer, drove a taxi, and his mother, once a teacher, cleaned houses. Their sacrifice was the silent, ever-present expectation in their small apartment, and Nikolai absorbed it completely. He pursued a Business Administration degree from UC Davis not out of passion, but out of a deep-seated need for stability and a desire to repay his parents' struggle with tangible success.\n\nHis career path was a straight, steep line. Hired by a prestigious downtown consulting firm right out of college, he quickly proved his worth. Nikolai is methodical and sharp, capable of deconstructing a company\u2019s logistical nightmare and presenting a solution in a clean, convincing PowerPoint. His six-figure income and role as a management consultant were the fulfillment of his family\u2019s American dream.\n\nThe turning point came at 29, with the dissolution of a three-year relationship. His ex-girlfriend\u2019s parting words, that he was meticulously managing every part of his life except his own happiness, struck a nerve. The critique echoed a quiet, growing dissatisfaction within him. He was solving problems for faceless corporations but felt utterly directionless himself.\n\nNow 30, Nikolai lives a life of disciplined routine in a modern Hayes Valley apartment. His 4.8-mile commute on the Muni Metro is a buffer between his two worlds: the sterile, high-stakes environment of his office and the quiet solitude of his home. While professionally social, his personal connections have dwindled since the breakup, limited to a few college friends.\n\nHis hope is a seed, secretly watered late at night on his laptop. He spends hours researching craft distilling, fascinated by the blend of science and artistry. His dream is to open a small-batch distillery in Dogpatch or the Bayview, creating a unique gin using Californian botanicals\u2014a fusion of his new home with a nod to his Russian heritage. He longs to build something tangible, to trade corporate strategy for a craft of his own, and finally define success on his own terms."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was twelve, riding in the back of the taxi after his father finished a long shift. The streetlights of the Richmond smeared through the foggy window. He watched his father\u2019s hands on the wheel\u2014the knuckles raw, a grease stain under one nail. He knew those were an engineer's hands, now gripping a vinyl wheel instead of a blueprint. The weight of that sacrifice settled in his chest, a silent promise he made to himself: he would make it worth it. This was the moment his ambition became a debt.\n\n2.\nAt eighteen, in a fluorescent-lit UC Davis computer lab, Nikolai stared at the list of majors. His cursor hovered briefly over History, a flicker of genuine interest. Then, decisively, he clicked \"Business Administration.\" There was no joy in the choice, only a cold sense of purpose. It felt like closing a door on a part of himself he hadn't yet met. This was the first major decision he made not for himself, but for the life his parents envisioned for him. His path was now set.\n\n3.\nHe was 26. The partners were applauding his takedown of a logistics problem for a billion-dollar client. Framed by the panoramic window of the boardroom, the city glittered below. He saw the Transamerica Pyramid, the Bay Bridge\u2014all the symbols of success he\u2019d strived for. He felt a spreadsheet in his mind click into place: Objective Achieved. But inside, there was only a sterile quiet. The victory felt like it belonged to someone else, a well-executed role he was only playing. The promised satisfaction was nowhere to be found.\n\n4.\nHis Hayes Valley apartment felt surgically clean when she said it. She stood by the door, her keys on the counter between them. \"You manage everything, Kolya. The project plans, the portfolio, this apartment... everything but your own happiness.\" The words weren't angry, just exhausted. They bypassed his defenses and landed with surgical precision. For the first time, his meticulously constructed life felt not stable, but fragile and hollow. Her leaving wasn't the wound; her diagnosis was. It was a truth he could no longer manage away.\n\n5.\nMonths after the breakup, at 2 AM, he fell down an internet rabbit hole. He landed on a documentary about a small distillery. He watched the copper still gleam, the clear spirit dripping, the founder talking about botanicals and mash bills with a reverent passion. It was a fusion of precise engineering and wild artistry. In that moment, a quiet hum started in his chest. It was a tangible process, a craft. He pictured a bottle, his own creation. The spreadsheet in his mind was replaced by a recipe. It was hope."
